    <item>
      <title>And Along Came a Spider</title>
      <author> GreenEyedGal </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1854269/and-along-came-a-spider/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1854269-and-along-came-a-spider/chapter/1854273/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">3ddb6f9b4b45439b9c3e0bc329c8628bdff186df</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 17 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Peter Parker was just your average, mild-mannered teenager. He excelled academically, and not so much socially. But what mattered to him most was his family-- his Uncle Ben and Aunt May. One night, after attending a science exhibition, Peter finds his life changed forever.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1854269-and-along-came-a-spider/chapter/1854273/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Bite Night&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;“Get lost, bookworm!” Flash Thompson barked as he flipped the mild-mannered Peter Parker’s books to the ground, followed only by the raucous laughter of his ever-present gang of goonish jocks. “Don’t you have a chemistry set or something to go to and play with, Parker?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As Peter slowly trudged to his locker, he wondered why Flash picked on him so much. Peter theorized that it was because Flash knew how superior Peter’s intelligence was compared to his own and felt threatened. Of course, a buffoon such as Flash would be jealous of the person that had the top grades in every single class (except PE). It was only unfortunate that for now, Flash, being bigger and stronger, found it easy to bully the relatively puny Peter. But Peter knew, he knew very well, that one day he’ll have his just desserts. One day he’ll show them all, he thought, he’ll show them, and they’ll all be sorry. Secretly, Peter reveled in that thought of his. It was all he could do to endure the constant bullying, isolation, and ridicule he received from his peers.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As he finally got to his locker, he heard a voice he knew very well start to berate Flash.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Why can’t you just leave the poor guy alone, Flash?” It was Betty Brant, the most popular girl in their grade. And Flash’s girlfriend. And being Flash’s girlfriend, she was one of the few people who could give Flash a talking-to and leave him cowed. “What did Peter Palmer ever do to you, huh?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“It’s Parker, actually. Peter Parker,” Peter meekly corrected.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Flash took sight of him once again, seemingly even more annoyed than he was earlier. He started marching to Peter, making their difference in size even more apparent.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Did you say something, Parker?” Somehow, Flash always managed to speak his surname with such venom.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Betty clung onto Flash’s humongous arm, seemingly trying to pull her behemoth boyfriend from Peter. “Flash, I told you to lay off him!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah, Flash, why don’t you use your ears for once?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Those words escaped Peter’s mouth before he even realized it. He didn’t know where it came from, but a part of him felt a certain sense of thrill from finally telling Flash off for once. But that newfound bravado backfired as Flash pulled Peter towards him by his collar.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh yeah? So, you finally opened your big mouth, eh? You want me to shut you up? For good?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peter replied once again without thinking, adrenaline seemingly pushing him on, “You think a beating from you can keep me down? Ha! Wanna bet?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But before anything more could happen, Betty managed to squeeze herself between the two, pushing them away from each other. “Boys, boys, please! Can you not let your machismo win out? You’re causing a scene.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m going to cause more than a scene when I get my hands on him, I tell you that Betts.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Flash Thompson, you will do no such thing!” Betty screamed out, pulling Flash away from Peter. “Now, leave him alone before you do something rash. You’re lucky there weren’t any faculty around, you know that?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Flash let Peter go, fixing himself as he did so. Wow, such a model student, Peter thought to himself. “You’re lucky, Betty was here, Parker. Now scram!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With that, Peter made a beeline for the nearest exit, only just noticing Betty giving him a slight smile as she waved him off. Flash was right for once. He really &lt;em&gt;was&lt;/em&gt; lucky Betty was there to get Flash to calm down. Peter wasn’t sure what got into him earlier, talking back to Flash like that, but now that the adrenaline was wearing off, he was feeling more and more thankful to Betty.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Just the sheer fact that she would defend him like that made the bullying he just endured feel a bit less painful. Even &lt;em&gt;if&lt;/em&gt; she couldn’t remember his name properly. What a girl as nice as her sees in Flash (the bully he was) to be with him, Peter will never understand.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In a way, Betty was Peter’s ideal girl. She was pretty, of course, with a great smile that always made Peter melt a bit when he saw it. And unlike the other girls in their grade like Liz Allen, she was nice and friendly to boot, usually standing up for the little guy like Peter himself. Traits which made her popularity a no-brainer.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And sometimes, while Peter wouldn’t admit it out loud, he was jealous of Betty. A part of him wished he was more like her. He lamented the fact that in most respects, he was the complete opposite of her. Unlike her, Peter was aloof, friendless— different. For as long as he could remember, Peter never really felt like he fit in with the other kids his age. Something about him felt different from them. Despite his intellect, he could never really figure out what caused him to be so different from his peers. Whenever he saw the people around him, they all seemed so self-assured, so in tune with themselves. Compared to them, Peter felt like a stranger in his own body, like something about him was… mis-aligned. Something was… wrong.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;As soon as school ended, Peter immediately made his way back home. All his other peers usually hung out after class (especially on weekends like it was now), going to here-or-there, the kind of places Peter can only ever imagine going to since no one ever invited him. Instead, aside from the occasional visit to the library or the science lab, Peter almost always went directly home. There, he would usually find his beloved Aunt May and Uncle Ben. For all his life, they were the only ones there for him. They took care of him after his parents died, raised him like the child they never had. He never wanted for more. Peter always strove to make them happy, he wanted to make them proud of him always, it was his one selfless desire. Peter cared for no one else other than them. The rest of the world can hang for all he cares, because to him, these two &lt;strong&gt;were&lt;/strong&gt; his world.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Peter! You’re home early,” Aunt May greeted him with a smile. “You’re just in time, I was just having a chat with Anna from next door, you remember her, right Petey?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Anna Watson. Our next-door neighbor and Aunt May’s best friend. Of course, Peter knew her. She and Aunt May would meet up so often for coffee or tea that she was practically in the Parker residence every day.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, she came by today and she was talking about how her niece would be moving in soon with her,” Aunt May continued. “She’s going to be transferring to your school too, so we thought that maybe we could have you two meet. You could show her around town, your school—”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No thanks Aunt May,” Peter quickly cut her off. He had much better things to do, he thought, “I’m going to be busy with the science fair next month and you know how it is.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aunt May frowned at his response. But she knew how important his projects were to Peter. “Alright, I’ll just tell her you’re busy. I hope your project goes well.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You know me Aunt May, it’ll blow everyone’s socks off at the fair,” Peter replied as he made his way to his bedroom.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As he put down his bag, ready to work on his project, Peter noticed something on his desk. Right beside the microscope his aunt and uncle gave him on his last birthday was a flyer along with tickets to a science exhibition happening that night.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Surprise, dear!” Aunt May suddenly spoke up behind him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Aunt May?! What’s this?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aunt May smiled at Peter, delighted at his excitement, “Your Uncle Ben saw the flyer a few days ago and he thought you’d be delighted to go. So, we decided to buy tickets so we could see the exhibition. We wanted to keep it a surprise, a reward for how hard you’ve been working at school lately.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peter looked at the flyer. What a coincidence! It was going to be an exhibition on atomic science, perfectly in-line with what he planned to work on for his science fair project. He couldn’t help but smile at the thought of seeing all those machines he would usually never be able to see elsewhere. Peter rushed to his Aunt May, giving her a big hug in his delight.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“My, Peter, I knew you’d be happy, but I never expected a hug,” Aunt May said as she giggled, “When was it that you last gave hugs like these? And here I thought you’d be like those other teenagers. Too ‘cool’ for hugs.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peter blushed a bit, even he was taken aback by what he did. But he can’t deny that hugging his Aunt May again felt good. “You know I’ve never been much like those other kids anyway, Aunt May. Sometimes a hug or two is cool too.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well, maybe save some of the hugging for your Uncle Ben too. He was the one who bought the tickets after all. That reminds me. We should probably get ready to go. He told me he’d just meet us there and we probably shouldn’t keep him waiting for long.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Petey!” Uncle Ben was beaming when he saw Peter and May arrive at the exhibition, “Here I was, scared you and May would never come. What, too busy to hang with the old man now?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peter immediately felt a sense of ease as soon as he saw his Uncle Ben. “You know I’d never miss out on a day with you, Uncle Ben. Especially with Aunt May here too.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Wouldn’t you rather hang out with friends of yours from school rather than a couple of old folk like us?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Peter laughed at that. What a suggestion, he thought to himself. “Like any of those lunkheads would ever get caught dead here.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Peter!” May said aghast.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Gee, sorry Aunt May. I guess I got a bit carried away there.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Don’t be too hard on him, May. The boy’s just letting off steam. Aintcha, Petey?” Uncle Ben said as he patted Peter on the back. Peter couldn’t help but compare his uncle’s pats to the way Flash would shove him at school. Unlike Flash who leaves Peter feeling useless and weak, Uncle Ben’s pats makes him feel stronger than ever— like he could take on the entire world. “Is it just me or are you getting bigger son? Been working out those muscles behind my back?” Uncle Ben joked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“You know the only muscle I’ve ever worked out in my life is my brain. And I can’t wait to work it out even more tonight. Thanks so much Uncle Ben!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Anything for you, Pete. Anything for you.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Aunt May pointed towards an exhibition hall. “Oh, look at that dear. It seems a presentation’s starting. You wouldn’t want to miss that, right Peter?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Behind some railings, a scientist stood beside two gigantic pieces of machinery, both topped with a bright-red array on the end. The machines slowly hummed to life as the scientist was finishing up his opening address. “— And now for a demonstration of how we can control radioactive rays here in the laboratory.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As Peter stared transfixed at the marvels in front of him, he quickly forgets the taunts he received at school— a relic of a different world, it seemed, as he is soon transported into the fantastic world of atomic science! But as the experiment began, no one, not Peter, not the scientists, noticed a tiny spider descending from the ceiling on an almost invisible stand of thread, right in the middle of the radioactive rays. And after being blasted by an amazing amount of radiation, the spider soon fell from its web of life and destiny onto young Peter Parker’s hand. In shock, Peter tried to swat the irradiated arachnid away but not before it managed to bite the young man; imbuing him with its venom before life ebbs from its irradiated body.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yowch!” That was the only thing Peter managed to say, getting the attention of the entire room in front of him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Is anything the matter, young man?” One of the scientists asks from behind the railings.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But before Peter could respond, he felt a sudden wave of dizziness overtake him. A strange throbbing sensation pulsed in his mind, as if it was tearing itself open. He felt short of breath, like his lungs were rejecting air. He soon stumbled forward, buckling under his own weight, and as he finally saw black, he felt a big, strong arm underneath him, supporting him as he fell to the ground.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;When Peter woke up, he found himself back in his bed. Was that all a dream? No, it felt all too real. He felt his hand throb, the same hand the spider bit, so he brought it to his face to inspect it. Yup, there it was. A big, red, throbbing welt where the spider bit into him. So, everything did happen. He was back home, so it probably wasn’t dangerous, or else he’d be in the hospital by now. It was probably just a common house spider, spooked by the experiment. And not only did Peter black out like a wuss, he missed the exhibition too! Hopefully Flash never hears about this, or else he’d have a field day with me, Peter thought to himself.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As he continued to inspect his hand, he noticed something strange about it. For some reason, it looked smaller. Maybe the bite was so big it caused an optical illusion? No, it wasn’t just his hand that felt strange; his entire body felt off. It was like that time Uncle Ben took him camping, the way his muscles ached the day after carrying huge bags, more of a workout that he usually did. But the pain felt numbed at the same time. Like he could breathe easier than he ever could, an immense strength seemingly brewing from somewhere inside him, a strange tense feeling just wanting to burst out. Peter had never felt like this before in his life.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Wanting to inspect this strange feeling further, he stood up from his bed, probably faster than he should have as he felt his blood rushing to his head, causing a momentary headache. As he stumbled back onto his bed, he felt more weird sensations. He felt strangely heavy in some areas, like his center of mass had shifted just enough that his balance felt off. He looked down and noticed that his chest and hips looked swollen. Maybe the spider really was venomous and it only affected him now? In that case, he should probably tell his aunt and uncle about this so he can be taken to the hospital before anything else happens.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;As he stumbled towards the door, he saw a figure from the corner of his eye. It was a girl. A pretty cute girl, if he had to say. Peter could see her clearly for some reason, despite the fact that he wasn’t wearing his glasses. And it looked like she was walking to the same direction as Peter. Startled, he stood up, and the girl copied him. Looking at her more, Peter felt a twinge of recognition in her face. She looked like someone he knew. Those eyes, that nose… she looked like the woman in the picture he kept in his desk drawer. This mysterious girl looked like his mother!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With such a strange sight in front of him, he could only utter the word, “Mom?” before noticing the girl in the mirror doing the same thing. The word rang in his ears, ringing in a voice he didn’t recognize. The word came from his mouth, but the voice wasn’t his. He never had the deepest voice, but the sound he heard himself produce sounded more like how it used to be before his adam’s apple dropped. Maybe even a bit lighter than that actually. Surprised by the strange voice that came from his mouth, he brought his hand up to his throat, with the girl in front of him copying him once again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No, the girl wasn’t copying him. As he finally started to fully wake up, as he finally got his bearings, he remembered what was across the bed, beside the door he was trying to get to: the wall mirror hanging on his closet door. He wasn’t seeing a girl copying him. He was seeing himself reflected in the mirror. What he’s been looking at this entire time, the girl that looked like his mother. It was him.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Before he can catch himself, his legs gave out beneath him and he fell onto the floor with a loud *thump*. Not knowing what else to do, his voice escaped him as he screamed out in shock, louder than he’s ever done in his life.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And as Uncle Ben and Aunt May burst into their darling nephew’s room, they too were startled to find this strange girl crying on the foot of Peter’s bed, in Peter’s clothes, staring at them with fear and worry in her eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Uncle Ben, Aunt May, what happened to me?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
