      <title>Noel Love and Claire St. Onge: PPE Guidelines For Archival Preservation And CFNM Encounters</title>
      <author> CharliJae </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1834593/noel-love-and-claire-st-onge-ppe-guidelines-for-archival-preservation-and-cfnm-encounters/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1834593-noel-love-and-claire-st-onge-ppe-guidelines-for-archival-preservation-and-cfnm-encounters/chapter/1841135/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">95274e35a40e1523c8976f1d1043446274cf04df</guid>
      <pubDate>Wed, 17 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Noel’s boss is…different. She’s got a kink, maybe? And Noel needs to know.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1834593-noel-love-and-claire-st-onge-ppe-guidelines-for-archival-preservation-and-cfnm-encounters/chapter/1841135/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Panicked Flights and Roommate Chats&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;“I trust you’ve read up on our preservation procedures.” It wasn’t a question, and it certainly wasn’t an invitation to speak. “August-Olstead University’s policies are very clear.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I nodded, knowing better than to speak. I’d been hired to assist Dr. Claire St. Onge, our University’s Archival Collection and Preservation Director, instructor, and tenured terror.&lt;span class="Apple-converted-space"&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Her current project? Digitizing and transcribing. This project, though, she handled herself. The team who’d made the find trusted no one else with the material.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My task was to type and type until I reached the last line, then move on to the next page. She had an exacting schedule, and Dr. St. Onge wouldn’t countenance a slow pace. I was her fourth assistant this year—the others dropped out over her onerous WPM requirements.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Me? Oh, yeah, I was gonna crash out too, but I needed the money. My roommate, Cate, short for Hecate…actually, that’s her business. If she wants to share, that’s cool.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Let’s just focus on the facts. Living in Olstead, Texas wasn’t cheap. Century old suburban enclaves built around tiny arts universities and nestled between Central Texas WASP subdivisions had to keep up with the times.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I have bills to pay—WE have bills to pay. She’s making enough, but we need some extra cash to float us for the next few months, once we get over some sticker shock. It’s gender stuff, doctor bullshit.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That’s all! This is what we agreed to.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Which is why I was here after lying my ass off on my application to work under Dr. St. Onge. The pay was way better than the other positions, and the hours? Nights and weekends off—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Mr. Love, you’re not listening,” Dr. St. Onge declared. “Tell me what I just said.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I looked up at her, took in her form. She wasn’t too tall, and she liked to wear small heels. Always a sensibly long skirt, white pantyhose, a sweater vest, and a blouse with poofy sleeves and tight cuffs, tipped with cotton gloves. Her hair was always pulled back in a tight, high ponytail, and she wore a KN-95 mask like it was the hottest accessory. A faint fog in her glasses was visible at all times.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Which was a lot more visible now, her breaths sharp and controlled. “Mr. Love, I took you on because you claimed you could work efficiently and with little direction. Tell me I was wrong in that assessment.” Her voice was even, husky, always declarative.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Yes! Um, yes, you were wrong—I mean, your assessment…" I decided to cut my losses and just started typing.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sighing, she continued. "You have been above average, despite your less than stellar punctuality. I was informing you that you need to slow down. You are actually working too fast." Her eyes crinkled for a split second—a smile?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Thank you, Mr. Love. You’ll be here on time tomorrow.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Now, if you’ll excuse me, I’ll be at the scanner bed. I am not to be disturbed." She turned on her heel and stepped back into the scanner room.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Typing with the page in my peripheral, I risked a glance to my right, watching Claire—Dr. St. Onge—perform her work.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Checking her database, finding the book she was scanning, laying it out on the prep table.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She carefully opened it, knowing that the book would be dust soon, removed the page with just her hands—wow—centered the page, positioned the overhead camera, snapped a photo. Reviewing it on her monitor, she moved it minutely, and took another photo. Satisfied with her handiwork, she flipped the page over gently, and—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Stopped. In a panic, I turned all of my attention back to my transcription, which was riddled with typos.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Opening the door, I heard Dr. St. Onge breathing fast, almost frantic. “Mr. Love, I apologize for my abruptness, but I need to leave early today. I’ve received a call from a…concerned party, and they need to see me in-person immediately. Will you be alright closing up?” She asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Um, yeah. Is everything alright?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yes, of course,” she said.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I noticed she had a hand in her vest pocket. A streak of brown-gray dust was visible up to the elbow. “Anything I need to know?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Nothing you don’t already know. Just, please, make sure everything is locked.” She exhaled big, and regained some composure. “You will have things properly locked and prepared for the next day.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right,” I said, giving her a nod.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Thank you. Now, if you will excuse me…” she looked at the floor, then bolted away at a walk almost as fast as a run.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Once she was gone, I typed for another hour before taking my time closing up.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I stepped into the scanning room, checked the ventilation, the dehumidifier, double checked for breaches, then deactivated the scanning hardware. The room cooled considerably. How did she work in here without sweating?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There was a glove on the prep table. White cotton, stained from finger to palm. I gathered it up and held it in my hand. It was so small, unassuming. Why be weird about it?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Checking to confirm that I was the only person in the room, I held it to my nose sniffed it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Dust.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Dark, sweet perfume.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Stale, recycled air.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No sweat, but…&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The acrid sharpness was faded, almost gone, but there it was.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Latex.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Odd, but it made sense. Kept things clean, safe barrier, plentiful, good fit, sweaty hands, maybe some texture—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Not today. I needed to not get so cum-brained about this stuff. Not everything was some sort of secret sex signal. Sometimes people could just be wearing gloves because it provided them with comfort and, remember, they served practical uses—yes. Correct.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;That’s all this was.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I tossed the glove in the wastebasket, turned out the lights, and left for the evening.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Cate was making tacos!&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Sitting at our modest kitchen table, Cate listened to me regale her with tales of my workday.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“So you think she’s some kind of pervert?” Cate asked.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Aww, c’mon, that’s a bad faith interpretation.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Well,” she said, shrugging her narrow shoulders, “you did seem to jump to ‘sex thing’ almost immediately.” She laughed while she took another bite.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No! I said, ‘there is a chance that this could be a sign of the possibility of a sexual fixation’.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“World record hedging there, Noel.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I rolled my eyes.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Look, all I’m saying is that it was weird, okay? The glove got a little dirty, and she flipped out. And I smelled latex in it—that was probably the least unusual thing, honestly.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right, you just want your boss to be a—“&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I want everybody to be a pervert!” I exclaimed, half-joking. “Then we can all at least be honest with each other.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah…” Cate said. “I…just keep an eye on the mail. I’ve got some stuff coming in—it’s a secret. And they said ‘discreet packaging’, but you never know. Trans girl pervert stuff."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Is that a disclosure?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“No…it was just in case you see anything weird.” She shifted in her seat. Yes, she had secrets—we all did. But it wasn’t my place to pry. Still…I wondered, more now than before.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maybe it was the hormones.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;No—it was DEFINITELY the hormones.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Or it could just be Cate…Cate and the hormones…her lips, her cheeks, the rounded softness settling into her jawline.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Gorgeous.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It was just, like, her bangs, her hair, a black curly mane that had just gotten—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"And hey,” she continued, “did you maybe wanna go to the arcade sometime? Maybe this weekend?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Duh."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;We kept eating in silence. She was wearing a low cut top. Her collarbones were showing, defined and delicate on her pale skin, the ivy vines tattooed across them more vivid than usual.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She was engrossed in her e-reader, the pale light catching her cheeks, her blush now apparent.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I wondered why I was thinking like this. Well, I knew—didn’t I?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;It wasn’t unusual to be attracted to beautiful women.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But this one in particular?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She caught me looking. "Something up?" Her voice lessons made her sound…I dunno. It’s weird to describe it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"No, just admiring the view," I said, knowing the truth would deflect.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Aww, kidder, I know I’m not Noel Hot."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Cate always liked to note my bedtime companions had a habit of being ‘model hot’, which…okay—no matter what…look, it’s sorta true, but she’s being selective.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Okay, okay, but, hey—I know you wanted me to say something," I began, and her face started to lose color, "your voice sounds great."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The color returned, and then some. "Thanks, I’m glad you like it." Cate smiled, so big she hid it with her hand. “And stop, you’re embarrassing me.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;"Why? I like it. You’re probably about to meet somebody perfect. Need to compliment you before you disappear." I finished my last bite after saying that.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Did I regret it?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;I don’t like thinking in hindsight like that. It’s not 20/20, it’s just what happened.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What I do know is that Cate got a little upset at that, which, “hey, I didn’t mean it like…however you thought. I was just saying…you’re amazing. And whoever ends up with you is gonna he lucky.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She sniffled, just a tiny bit. Small enough for her to think I didn’t notice. “It’s fine! It’s fine. Getting used to people looking at me, and wishing it wasn’t as weird.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I get that. I can’t relate, but you can lean on me. And you’ve got buddies, right?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Cate swallowed her last bite. “Yeah.” She wiped her mouth, and picked up our plates. “I’ll load these up and head to bed. See you tomorrow.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Right,” I said, also getting up, picking up my water glass and slugging half of it. Nooo! Ice water! I got brain freeze.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;***&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What could I fucking say to her?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Nothing. I didn’t want to make it weird. She got self-conscious enough when she started. She didn’t want her fucking “platonic life-partner” worried about falling for her. That was what made it cool. We were open, we were fun, we were just friends, and there were no complicating factors. I was cool with it. She thought it was perfect.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Well, did she really?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;hr /&gt; &lt;p&gt;hey! Charli here. Thank you for reading! If you enjoyed this, check out my previous, completed novella, &lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1803371/dangerously-close-to-bearable/"&gt;Dangerously Close to Bearable&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;And stay tuned—I've got an epic science-fantasy action/adventure story in the wings as well.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
