      <title>Highland ghost stories</title>
      <author> deekaede </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1808593/highland-ghost-stories/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1808593-highland-ghost-stories/chapter/1817910/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">e4ef25477898885161f648acd1db7b48dd2da004</guid>
      <pubDate>Tue, 16 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;In our modern age, we have a proclivity towards believing that everything has a logical explanation. That all of the world can simply be explained, quantified, reified, and understood using simple means. We never give a thought about the old folktales and whether they were actually true in any way shape or form. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;     We also, most certainly, never think that what we took for granted could be upended in such a world-shattering way. Herein is a story about one such person. Who stepped off the edge of what was known, and was logical. Young Ailis Gunn, returning home from abroad. Alone, meek, and totally ignorant of how big their world was about to come, and what changes awaited them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1808593-highland-ghost-stories/chapter/1817910/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;A seasoned beginning.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;            “Good afternoon young lady, do you have anything to declare?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            These were words spoken to a rather diminutive person standing at the customs desk of London Heathrow airport. The person in question stood approximately 170 centimeters in height, had shoulder length brown hair, brilliant blue eyes and an otherwise unremarkable face. Upon first glance, one would be forgiven for thinking them androgynous. This person, was Ailis Gunn, newly arrived from America.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;             “Um… no I don’t,” said Ailis, their cheeks glowing in embarrassment.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            Ailis’ eyes glanced downwards. Unable to quite meet the agents face. Their hand simply slid over their identification documents, without allowing another word to be spoken. They stood with one arm crossed over their chest, gripping their other arm with a somewhat uneasy expression.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            The customs agent eyed the documents that he was handed. With a bored look, he flipped through them, then stamped Ailis’ paperwork roughly before handing it all back.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            “Welcome back to the United Kingdom Miss Gunn. Enjoy your stay” the man finally said, before he beckoned the 18-year-old to move along.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Carefully, Ailis navigated the airport. They looked rather overwhelmed by the volume of people and the noise. Though, within a few minutes, Ailis’ expression eased as they seemed to adjust to the general pace and nature of the airport. Ailis’ eyes wandered across the boutiques and shops in the airport, seeming to take in the atmosphere.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          One in particular caught their eyes. It looked to be a rather upscale clothing store. Based upon the outfits on display, it was a women’s clothing store. Probably meant to appeal to tourists. Inside they could see various mannequins adorned in tastefully selected outfits. The current seasons fashion was visible to all, practically begging people to come inside and buy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;However, one look at the price tag was enough to keep Ailis from acting on any impulses. But they had to admit, the dress on a mannequin did actually look rather cute. Especially as it had been accessorized quite smartly. All in all, it was one a very cute outfit in particular which caused Ailis to feel some measure of envy. Compared to the outfit the mannequin wore, Ailis realized, their own choice of attire was rather boring.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Ailis gave a troubled look at this thought. However, they seemed to press the intrusive thought out of their head. Their somewhat confused expression gave way to a look of annoyance. Instead of seemingly dwelling on this troubling thought, and as if to chase off this uncomfortable feeling, they pushed on to the Heathrow Terminal train. The destination: Kings Cross station in Central London.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Later, Ailis found themselves outside of Paddington station in central London. Ailis took a moment to look down at a piece of printed out paper in their hand. According to their directions, they had only to walk northeast to the 501 and follow it until they reached Kings cross station. Ailis swelled their chest in absolute confidence a slightly smug smirk playing on their face. After all, they were quite the expert navigator if they did say so themselves. With this pride in their heart, and the gentle squeak of their luggage, they pressed on boldly.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Within 5 minutes Ailis came to the realization: they had no idea which way was north. Or even, most critically, where on god’s green earth they even were. Indeed, They had set off in the completely wrong direction. Shortly, they felt themselves growing ever more lost with each step. Their cheeks inflated into a slight pout as they came to realize their rather embarrassing situation.  &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;         But after 10 minutes of walking, they spied a rather spacious green area, then decided to make it their temporary destination. With a look of determination, and dragging their cumbersome luggage behind them, they glanced up at a sign that loomed overhead.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;           “Victoria gate, Hyde Park” said the sign on an ornate gate separating the noise and the bustle of the city from the tranquil looking park just beyond.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              Ailis’ head tilted as they read the sign. Their face registered some measure of recognition. They clearly didn’t have a clue as to why it sounded familiar but it would do as a resting spot. With a slight shrug of their shoulders, Ailis proceeded into the pleasant looking park.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          While they sat on a bench trying to figure out where they were, their eyes drifted around, surveying the scenery before them. It was a nice day by English standards. It was rather cool (by Ailis’ standards) at only 20 degrees Celsius; there was no wind blowing, the sun was beaming radiantly, and families were enjoying the lake and surrounding greenery.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Ailis stopped their gaze on a girl standing by her lonesome. Looking seemingly bored but gave it little thought. However, after a moment, they realized the girl was making eye contact with them. Which made them feel rather self-conscious and glanced away politely. Their gaze then settled back onto the crude map in their hand as they tried to figure out where they were precisely and where they needed to go.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          What Ailis didn’t know at that moment, was that their casual eye contact had roused the curiosity of the girl. She approached this lost person sitting on the bench. Who failed to notice her presence while they were busily studying the map.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          “Excuse me,” her voice called out, “but are you lost or something?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Ailis looked up from the map they were studying, then to the girl standing to their left. She was a young girl looked to be about 13 years old. Her faces was covered in light freckles, and her brown eyes were framed by a rather modest bob haircut.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Their cheeks flushed as he responded in a neutral voice which carried little in the way of masculinity, “I’m a little bit lost. I’m trying to find my way to Kings Cross station. But I seem to be going in the wrong direction I think…” Ailis’ expression gave way from curiosity to sheepishness, a light red tint playing across their cheeks.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          The girl’s curious expression slowly began to change. From a look of surprise to a look of pure joy.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          For a moment she stood silently, her face screwed up in a contemplative expression. Then, as if seeming to realize something, began talking.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;        “Where are you from?” she asked simply, giving Ailis an expectant look.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;         “Oh, I’m from the United States. It’s a country on the other side of the ocean. I’m here for college” Ailis responded absently.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          “Well, that explains it, everyone knows this is Hyde Park and Kings Cross station is the other way from here” she said while pointing out north.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Ailis let out a sigh of relief then stood up rather suddenly, looking much brighter than they had mere moments ago. They took a note of North, glanced around a little as if getting their bearings of east and west, then turned to look at the girl who helped them out.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;        “Thank you very much for your assistance,” they said, their voice trending slightly higher with emotion, “Had you not pointed the way, I might have become even more lost and missed my train.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;        “Train?” she said, “Where are you going?”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;        “Edinburgh Scotland” Ailis answered happily “I’m starting college there”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;        “Hoo… well I hope things go well for you. And please stay safe” the girl intoned.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;         She then stuck out her hand in a friendly manner. Realizing that she wanted to shake hands, Ailis happily returned the gesture. However, as their hands touched, Ailis gave a small look of surprise. The girls hand felt rather cool and damp to the touch. However, they quickly dismissed this as not really and of their business with a look of gratitude. After all, people all had their own circumstances.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;         “Thanks. You as well. And please, have a fantastic day” Ailis responded, having lapsed into a more friendly tone before turning back to the gate and setting off once again.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Had Ailis looked back, they would have seen the girl walk back towards the small pond, then, as someone crossed between, he and her, she would have vanished seemingly into thin air. However, in time with her disappearance, the waters of the pond were disturbed with ripples, as if something had leapt into them. Ailis had yet to realize it, but they had just had their first encounter with an Asrai. A type of Fae who lived in waters.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Ailis was also lucky in their encounter. The Asrai are considered a benevolent variety of Fae. Who are characterized as helpful water sprites who only ever hurt others when their own life is threatened. Had it been a malevolent sort of Fae, there was a chance that Ailis might have had a very perilous encounter. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          After the young girl pointed them in the right direction, Ailis eventually was able to locate Kings Cross station. After having raced across London to get there, they leaned over, panting slightly to catch their breath. Then they stood up to look at the departure boards to find their train. Upon seeing that it was still some time from departure, Ailis gave a smile of relief. They still had some time to go before it left.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            Happily, Ailis walked to the terminal, then got themselves situated on the train. It was a single berth, and thankfully they weren’t sharing it with anyone. Ailis plopped down into the seat, then took out their phone. A simple and cheap looking thing. When they clicked it on, the only icon that showed was a music player. As they went to open it, they glanced briefly at the messages and phone calls tab but saw there were none.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;           Faced with his destination, Ailis allowed themself a moment of reprieve to consider his situation. Here he was, in his home country he barely knew, in a city he only dimly remembered, heading to a place they only ever visited once. He realized they were actually rather excited. Excited to see where his mother grew up, played, made friends, and fell in love. He was excited at the prospect of meeting new people, studying, and eventually getting a good job.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          Yet, underneath this excitement was a sense of unease. Worry at the same time that they would hate it, that they didn’t belong, that something bad would happen. That they would be stuck with nothing. Lost and alone in a strange place with nothing to support them. After a moment, Ailis let out a sigh as if to dismiss such thoughts. After all, they didn’t really have any support back in the states to begin with. So, nothing here versus nothing there carried little fundamental difference.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;          More than that, they felt a deeper unease in their heart. They had no way of framing it with words. But there was a strong sense that something even bigger was wrong. Something they couldn’t frame with words. As if the very concept of the words Ailis used to describe themself were somehow wrong. As if they were deceiving themselves and trying to play a part they were not suited for.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            The problem, Ailis figured, was that after the death of their parents, they had gone into a period of isolation. Not wanting to speak to others, not wanting to really interact with others, and simply wanting to be left alone. When Ailis had left the states, the only person they talked regularly to were the social workers. In a way, the trauma of the accident and their parents death had deprived them of their teenage years. Years in which one learns how to socialize with their peers, begins to understand what kind of people they like, what their type of preferences are in dating, and firm up their own sense of self identity.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            Ailis had none of that. All that they knew, was that it was something they would have to work on. Like this meekness and inability to really address when people gendered them as a woman. For some reason that they couldn’t explain, it felt inappropriate to correct them. And the confusion that this feeling caused left them feeling unsettled and worried.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;           As they contemplated this, their gaze drifted to the outside, their reflection clearly visible. To them. Their features were normal. Auburn hair that was a little long but well kept, turquoise blue eyes, hair sitting just off his shoulders, and his face was just… neutral? Right? They couldn’t quite place it, but they did have a feeling that even now they should perhaps be a little different...&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;            With the train’s movement however, they allowed themselves to relax a little. their hand idly tapped the seats handrest in a rhythmic pattern. As if one hand were playing the piano. Which, in a way, it was. It happened to be one of their more beloved hobbies. Playing American songs on the Piano.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              When they were younger, they dealt with the aftermath of his parents’ death by indulging in the last thing their mother had taught them, which was how to play music. Ailis came to love it and regarded memories of sitting by her while learning different chords, how to move their thin and delicate hands and fingers separately of each other and memorizing songs that she had taught them.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;              In a way, they had come to see music as a way of holding dearly onto something precious that they had lost so many years before. It had, in a way, come to eclipse their other love of astronomy. Though they were as yet unaware of such a thing having happened. Instead, they blithely believed one was more important than the other, and that they only had the option to master one and that the other would be neglected. Pity the foolish child for such narrow views…&lt;br /&gt; &lt;br /&gt;              Lost in these murky thoughts, they watched idly as the train slowly departed the London metro area, the high rises and built-up city giving way to first suburban neighborhoods and town squares, to eventually rural countryside. The train plowing along at a high-speed pace. Taking them closer and closer to their mothers birthplace and the location of their college.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;End of First Chapter&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Post script:&lt;/em&gt; This entire story was almost something else entirely. However, as I began working on it, I was nudged in a slightly different direction with the story by a few friends suggestions. Which helped to really bring the story into focus. A lot of my references for the original story will, however, wind up getting used again. This is going to be a bit of a slow burn novel and as of writing this, I only really have about 6 chapters dialed in as to what I want them to contain, and a larger overview of where the story is going. If you've taken the time to read this, I appreciate you taking the time. If you wish to leave suggestions, I am open to them. However, there are some formatting issues which appeared when I transferred this over to scribblehubs interface. It is annoying. But now that I know of them. I can take preventative measures to ensure it doesn't happen in the future. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
