      <title>Lockpick the Shut-in</title>
      <author> zedisnotdead </author>
      <link>https://www.scribblehub.com/series/1805303/lockpick-the-shutin/</link>
      <comments>https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1805303-lockpick-the-shutin/chapter/1805305/#comments</comments>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">d5b212659c517360bfffcd11927dd342ac22c26a</guid>
      <pubDate>Fri, 05 Sep 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>&lt;div class="wi_fic_desc" property="description"&gt;&lt;p&gt;Violet's lifestyle is very unhealthy, living day to day being a total mess, until her long time online friend Rose decides to move in with her. Unexpectedly, she starts slowly but surely fixing not just her habits, but herself. They are friends, but there's no way just a friend would do this much for her... right?&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;hr&gt;&lt;h3&gt;&lt;a href="https://www.scribblehub.com/read/1805303-lockpick-the-shutin/chapter/1805305/"&gt;&lt;div class="chapter-title"&gt;Chapter 1: Entryway&lt;/div&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;div class="chp_raw" id="chp_raw"&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;“Uuuungh...”&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The groan could barely be heard from the mountain of pillows, plushies and duvets on the bed. The alarm that Violet set on her phone was blaring one of her favourite video game songs that, regardless of what pleasant memories she once associated with it, now brought only dread of the oncoming day. A singular arm popped out from the pillow fort, and lazily, yet with a calculated precision of someone that’s done this exact same movement every single day, turned off the alarm. She fully emerged from the safety of her bed, grabbed her phone, and then proceeded to disable the other 6 alarms that she’s set up to make sure not to miss the morning meeting at work.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;With a throbbing headache brought on by nothing in particular, and her back and limbs hurting for no apparent reason (definitely not because she’s been sleeping on a not particularly comfortable sofa bed), Violet didn’t as much walk to the bathroom, more like her head was dragging the rest of her body along via a tentative peace agreement established with the legs. She flung one of her arms onto the light switch, illuminating the bathroom. She had black hair that looked shockingly well taken care of... Usually. She hadn’t washed it in the last 3 days after all. Her eyes betrayed her weariness, as they were “adorned” with dark eye bags. She splashed some water on her face, and looked at herself to see if she looked enough like a functional member of society. Violet was, in terms of attractiveness, average (though she’d burst out laughing and deprecate herself several levels lower) – the fat on her face hid the more masculine parts that she always wanted to get rid of, just like she got rid of the facial hair. Thankfully, she was functional enough that she managed to book laser facial hair removal, and thanks to that, she only had a few patches left, that only necessitated a slight touch-up in the morning, rather than the depression-filled Sisyphean task that it used to be. It’s not like she thought she was ugly, she just... Didn’t feel much at all about her appearance. Her diet’s always been an afterthought, more like whatever she wanted to eat at the time than anything that would balance her nutrition. Thankfully meds curbed some of her appetite, but she still sported a big belly – one of the few upsides of her weight was the added “material” for the hormones to do their work, as she had a couple of nice looking boobs just above her stomach (you know, where boobs usually are).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Having done her “morning routine”, Violet got back to her cluttered room, found the T-shirt she’s only been wearing for the past half a week, and put it on. There wasn’t much of anything else to do in her room, like make the bed, or open the curtains, as those haven’t been opened since she’s had anyone over. She opened the dinky laptop her employer gave her to do work on, and opened up Zoom to the daily morning work meeting. It was just a bunch of busywork they had to do to keep the product owners happy, but at least she didn’t have to talk much – just mention what she’s been working on since yesterday and report on progress. Fat load of good that did for Violet’s mood, with her migraine worsening the more she had to listen to the incredibly stupid questions management was asking the development team.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“God, like trying to explain Microsoft Word to a rat.” she muttered under her nose, not before checking if her microphone was muted. Anything, as long as she was getting paid, and didn’t have to leave her house. She’d heard on the news about how companies are trying to get their employees back to the offices and she couldn’t help but groan in frustration at all the excuses they were giving, about “teamwork” and “company culture” – no, you just want someone to micromanage, you bunch of—&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Alright team, let’s get some work done. Have a good weekend!”&lt;br /&gt; “Bye!”&lt;br /&gt; “Bye!”&lt;br /&gt; “Bye!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh thank god, the meeting is over.” she unmuted herself, muttered her own “bye”, and with a swift shortcut left the meeting. Even if it was only 15 minutes, talking to people (especially business people) felt like it took away days of her life. She opened her favourite code editor to at least pretend like she’s gonna do some work done, then turned on her personal computer. One of the perks of being a developer is the fat salary, and that let her put together a pretty gnarly rig, which could handle any game without breaking a sweat. Violet opened all of her usually used programs – a web browser, Steam, Discord and Thunderbird (she thinks email is very underrated, all the spam notwithstanding).&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;She then noticed something on Discord, a red circle with a “6” in it over the avatar of one of her friends.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;pre&gt;alright just got off the train, heres hoping i dont get lost&lt;br /&gt;uhhhh right i get off at main street right?&lt;br /&gt;mateeeee&lt;br /&gt;oh wait i think i know where to go&lt;br /&gt;dude i’m out front&lt;br /&gt;dont make me waitt&lt;/pre&gt; &lt;p&gt;The last two messages were timestamped merely 2 minutes ago, and not shortly after reading the last “t”, Violet heard a doorbell. In half a second, her brain went into overdrive, and connected the two dots. She bolted up, nearly tripping on some laundry that was sitting on the floor, and ran to the door, opening it with the urgency of someone running away from a fire.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Hi roommate!”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;On the other side of the door stood a girl not much shorter than Violet, with beautiful, wavy, burnt blonde hair that reached her shoulders. She wasn’t wearing any makeup, but she was so pretty that anyone could’ve been fooled she was. She was wearing a yellow button up shirt with floral patterns and jorts, and on her side was a pretty hefty suitcase.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Oh god Rose that looks heavy I really should’ve woken up earlier and picked you up I’m so sorry I’m a total mess—” Violet started profusely apologizing to her friend Rose, partially because she genuinely felt sorry, and partially because this was the first time she’s seen her in real life, the two have never really shared photos of themselves.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I know how you are in the mornings, so it’s really no big deal! Plus...” Rose pulled out a bag laden with snacks “...I wanted to surprise you! We got lots to celebrate after all! Oh but... You might want to put some clothes on.”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Reality hit Violet like a dump truck, as she realized she was holding the door wide open while wearing boxer shorts and a very, very stained white shirt.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“Yeah I probably should shouldn’t I...”&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Rose stepped in, put the bag on the ground, and gave Violet a very big, tight hug, nearly burying herself in her chest.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;“I’m so excited to finally be living with you!”&lt;br /&gt; “M-me too...” wow holy shit did all girls smell this good? Also, she was definitely &lt;em&gt;way &lt;/em&gt;too close for it to be just a normal friend hug. Violet brushed those thoughts off with a simple reasoning – there is no way anyone would be into her.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/div&gt;</description>
